         <desc type="abstract" xml:id="abstract390-1">
        <quote>
          <placeName>Caesaream
               Palaestinae</placeName>
        </quote>, <quote>
          <placeName>Caesarea</placeName>
        </quote>,  and <quote>
          <placeName>Caesarea Palestinae</placeName>
        </quote> are directly attested at <persName role="author">Theodosius</persName>, <title xml:lang="en" ref="" type="uniform" level="m">The Holy Land</title> <ref target="#bib390-1">4.7-4.12</ref>. This passage was written circa <origDate notBefore="0510" notAfter="0540" period="#byzantine">510-540 CE</origDate> possibly in <origPlace ref="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/687995">Palestine</origPlace>.</desc>
         <desc type="context">We know almost nothing about Theodosius, who wrote an account of his
            pilgrimage to the Holy Land in the first half of the 6th century, at some point between
            the reigns of Anastasius and Justinian. His short narrative, which includes brief but
            vivid details of geography, religion, history, and local legend, focused on Jerusalem
            but extends outward into Mesopotamia, Syria, and Asia Minor. His itinerary advances west
            from Jerusalem to the coast, north to Caesarea, and northeast into the Galilee.</desc>
         <ab type="edition" xml:lang="la" xml:id="quote390-1" source="#bib390-1">
        <anchor xml:id="testimonia-390.la.1" corresp="testimonia-390.en.1"/>De Diospoli in Ioppen milia XII, ubi sanctus Petrus resuscitavit sanctam
            Tabitham; ubi et cetus iactavit se victo Ionam. De Ioppe ad <placeName>Caesaream
               Palaestinae</placeName> milia XXX; ibi baptizatus est domnus Cornelius a domno Petro
            et martyrizatus est. De <placeName>Caesarea</placeName> usque in Diocaesarea milia XXX;
            inde fuit Symon magus. De Diocaesarea usque in Canan Galilaea milia V.<note type="textual">Ed. Geyer 1965</note>
        <note type="textual"/>
        <note type="discussion"/>
        <note type="corrigenda"/>
        <idno type="CTS-URN"/>
        <ref/>
      </ab>
         <ab type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:id="quote390-2" source="#bib390-2">
        <anchor xml:id="testimonia-390.en.1" corresp="testimonia-390.la.1"/>It is 12 miles from Diospolis to Joppa, where St. Peter brought St.
            Tabitha back to life; that is also where the defeated whale threw out Jonah. It is 30
            miles from Joppa to <placeName>Caesarea Palestinae</placeName>; there lord Cornelius was
            baptized by lord Peter and martyred. It is 30 miles from <placeName>Caesarea</placeName>
            as far as Diocaesarea; Simon Magus was there. It is 5 miles from Diocaesarea as far as
            Cana in Galilee. <note type="translation">Trans. J. L. Rife </note>
        <note type="discussion"/>
        <note type="corrigenda"/>
        <idno type="CTS-URN"/>
        <ref target=""/>
      </ab>
